The article discusses the progress of tax reform in the United States. It highlights the need for modernizing the tax code, which has been outdated, onerous, and inefficient. The Senate and the House have passed different versions of the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act, and Republican leaders are confident in reaching a consensus and sending a bill to President Trump by the end of the year. The article argues that the current high corporate tax rate in the US is a hindrance to employment and wages, and a decrease in the rate would lead to positive outcomes for working families. Additionally, the tax reform legislation provides benefits for middle-class taxpayers, such as doubling the standard deduction, increasing the child tax credit, and lowering individual tax rates. The article concludes by stating that modernizing the tax code will have long-term benefits for the American economy and middle-class workers.